1
00:00:06,279 --> 00:00:07,200
Good morning, everybody.

2
00:00:07,740 --> 00:00:09,703
Hello and welcome to our panel, Ripple Effect,

3
00:00:09,783 --> 00:00:11,585
How Women in Games Initiatives Make a Difference.

4
00:00:12,066 --> 00:00:13,988
My name's Stephanie Fisher and I'm the panel chair.

5
00:00:14,889 --> 00:00:15,730
Just want to remind everyone,

6
00:00:15,771 --> 00:00:16,852
please turn off your cell phones

7
00:00:17,112 --> 00:00:19,916
and please fill out your speaker evaluations after this.

8
00:00:20,941 --> 00:00:24,825
presentation. And before we start, I just want to let everyone know how we're actually going to run

9
00:00:24,865 --> 00:00:30,072
the panel. So all of us up here got our start in games via a community run wig initiative. And

10
00:00:30,112 --> 00:00:34,718
we're each going to give a short micro talk on, so you can get a sense of who we are, what we do,

11
00:00:35,178 --> 00:00:38,562
and how we've gone, you know, from wig program participant to our current positions or

12
00:00:38,823 --> 00:00:39,764
something generally like that.

13
00:00:40,915 --> 00:00:45,417
After that, we'll have a conversation that's going to be focused on providing strategies

14
00:00:45,458 --> 00:00:49,239
and resources on how to get more women into games, as well as how to work towards creating

15
00:00:49,259 --> 00:00:50,880
a more diverse and inclusive industry.

16
00:00:51,941 --> 00:00:55,422
Post-panel will be in the wrap-up room, but we're only going to do that for ten minutes,

17
00:00:55,482 --> 00:00:59,344
and this is just for exchanging contact info and business cards, but please feel free to

18
00:00:59,384 --> 00:01:00,645
connect via email and Twitter, too.

19
00:01:02,833 --> 00:01:03,893
OK, so who am I?

20
00:01:03,913 --> 00:01:06,514
I am a gender and games researcher

21
00:01:06,574 --> 00:01:07,894
from York University in Toronto.

22
00:01:08,674 --> 00:01:10,674
I'm a co-lead for a research project

23
00:01:10,715 --> 00:01:14,775
called Refiguring Innovation in Games, or Refig for short.

24
00:01:15,355 --> 00:01:18,036
I also belong to a lost generation of women

25
00:01:18,136 --> 00:01:20,637
who played games growing up, but for a myriad of reasons

26
00:01:20,697 --> 00:01:22,817
didn't think they could have a career in this industry.

27
00:01:24,557 --> 00:01:26,238
Back then, when I was a child.

28
00:01:26,789 --> 00:01:30,673
There were not a lot, or none, no game developing or coding

29
00:01:30,713 --> 00:01:33,416
initiatives that specifically targeted women or girls.

30
00:01:33,956 --> 00:01:35,357
Nowadays, this is clearly not the case.

31
00:01:35,738 --> 00:01:37,199
There's a lot of programs where kids

32
00:01:37,219 --> 00:01:39,001
can learn how to make games and how

33
00:01:39,041 --> 00:01:41,604
they can learn how to code, both in person and online.

34
00:01:42,064 --> 00:01:43,365
These are just a handful.

35
00:01:45,848 --> 00:01:48,891
In 2011, I found myself managing one of these kids' game

36
00:01:48,931 --> 00:01:50,412
development camps at my university.

37
00:01:51,142 --> 00:01:52,882
And even though my role in this camp

38
00:01:52,962 --> 00:01:54,963
was as a manager and a curriculum developer,

39
00:01:55,283 --> 00:01:57,604
the kids would still ask me for programming

40
00:01:57,624 --> 00:02:00,245
or code-related questions when they needed help in Game Maker.

41
00:02:01,045 --> 00:02:02,786
And it sucked when I couldn't help them.

42
00:02:03,326 --> 00:02:05,166
I had to admit that I couldn't help them with their code.

43
00:02:05,307 --> 00:02:07,787
I felt like a poor role model for the girls in the camp who

44
00:02:07,807 --> 00:02:09,168
looked up to female staff members.

45
00:02:09,728 --> 00:02:11,549
I really wanted to learn how to make more games,

46
00:02:11,669 --> 00:02:13,669
but I was just at the start of my PhD.

47
00:02:14,410 --> 00:02:17,071
And between work and school and more work,

48
00:02:17,351 --> 00:02:18,831
that really left me with little time or money

49
00:02:18,871 --> 00:02:19,571
to do anything else.

50
00:02:21,498 --> 00:02:22,238
So what was I going to do?

51
00:02:24,179 --> 00:02:26,860
And what I can only describe as an incredibly stroke

52
00:02:26,900 --> 00:02:28,421
of good luck, my research partner

53
00:02:28,501 --> 00:02:31,402
forwarded me over information for a women in games program

54
00:02:31,422 --> 00:02:33,323
that was accepting applications in Toronto.

55
00:02:33,923 --> 00:02:36,004
This program is called the Difference Engine Initiative,

56
00:02:36,524 --> 00:02:38,725
and it sought to bring more women into the Toronto game

57
00:02:38,765 --> 00:02:41,266
scene by helping 12 aspiring game developers make

58
00:02:41,306 --> 00:02:43,527
their first game in six weeks for free,

59
00:02:44,008 --> 00:02:44,988
no experience required.

60
00:02:45,368 --> 00:02:45,648
Perfect.

61
00:02:46,810 --> 00:02:48,812
By the end of this program, I had made a game,

62
00:02:49,272 --> 00:02:50,433
but I had left with so much more.

63
00:02:50,453 --> 00:02:53,316
I was so inspired by the potential of this community

64
00:02:53,356 --> 00:02:56,339
program and so impressed by the women who were a part of it

65
00:02:56,459 --> 00:02:58,440
that I actually changed my dissertation topic

66
00:02:58,580 --> 00:03:00,662
from educational games to exploring

67
00:03:00,702 --> 00:03:02,204
the impact of WIG programs.

68
00:03:03,244 --> 00:03:05,386
So I'm not going to bore you with five years of research

69
00:03:05,406 --> 00:03:07,248
findings, because this is neither the time nor the place.

70
00:03:08,309 --> 00:03:10,731
But if I could sum it up in one ultimate takeaway sentence.

71
00:03:11,285 --> 00:03:13,447
It's that WIG initiatives that provides free support

72
00:03:13,467 --> 00:03:16,150
and training for adult women who want to make games

73
00:03:16,450 --> 00:03:18,592
not only gets more women into this industry,

74
00:03:18,953 --> 00:03:21,715
but also contributes to creating a diverse and inclusive game

75
00:03:21,755 --> 00:03:22,736
culture in the long run.

76
00:03:24,558 --> 00:03:25,359
Oops, sorry.

77
00:03:26,360 --> 00:03:29,262
So while that might be a really obvious statement to someone

78
00:03:29,302 --> 00:03:32,045
who's already engaged in community organization work,

79
00:03:32,085 --> 00:03:33,627
not everyone actually thinks this way

80
00:03:34,507 --> 00:03:36,169
or sees the value in WIG initiatives.

81
00:03:38,279 --> 00:03:40,620
Some people think that focusing on special interest groups,

82
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:42,561
like women in games, does not work

83
00:03:42,601 --> 00:03:45,503
towards cultivating a fair and equitable industry for everyone.

84
00:03:45,983 --> 00:03:47,244
And they actually say it's going to lead

85
00:03:47,264 --> 00:03:49,305
to further discrimination and division among us.

86
00:03:50,205 --> 00:03:52,386
So for example, in reference to the outcomes

87
00:03:52,527 --> 00:03:54,788
of the Difference Initiative specifically,

88
00:03:55,528 --> 00:03:57,249
these are some things that's been stated about it.

89
00:03:58,069 --> 00:04:00,691
Initiatives like the DEIs don't do an adequate job

90
00:04:01,031 --> 00:04:02,572
of addressing or actually treating

91
00:04:02,592 --> 00:04:06,514
the systemic biases that have made the games industry

92
00:04:06,554 --> 00:04:06,894
culture.

93
00:04:07,358 --> 00:04:08,759
less diverse, and less healthy.

94
00:04:09,779 --> 00:04:11,701
The DEI was designed as a creative space

95
00:04:11,761 --> 00:04:13,302
where people could challenge themselves,

96
00:04:13,842 --> 00:04:16,644
develop their abilities, and learn alongside each other

97
00:04:16,704 --> 00:04:18,385
in a warm and encouraging environment.

98
00:04:19,106 --> 00:04:21,187
Instead, it was viewed as a support group,

99
00:04:21,427 --> 00:04:23,649
underscored and necessitated by a reaction

100
00:04:23,689 --> 00:04:26,550
to an unequal social world where learning was secondary

101
00:04:26,590 --> 00:04:29,032
to the formation of bonds and relationships.

102
00:04:30,538 --> 00:04:32,459
That description of the Difference Engine Initiative

103
00:04:32,499 --> 00:04:34,499
was very surprising to the people who were actually in it.

104
00:04:35,880 --> 00:04:38,701
We certainly didn't feel that it was this failure in the way

105
00:04:38,721 --> 00:04:40,601
it was being described, especially

106
00:04:41,082 --> 00:04:43,442
when the second iteration of the Difference Engine Initiative

107
00:04:43,723 --> 00:04:46,423
received almost universal praise for being a great success.

108
00:04:47,164 --> 00:04:49,064
This visualization, which was created

109
00:04:49,104 --> 00:04:51,905
by the talented Yuna Li, also a Difference Engine alum

110
00:04:52,005 --> 00:04:54,086
and who's in the audience today, demonstrates

111
00:04:54,126 --> 00:04:56,807
the impact of the program mere months after it ended.

112
00:04:57,797 --> 00:05:00,199
It's a little small, but every node in here

113
00:05:00,239 --> 00:05:03,921
represents the games, community initiatives, employment

114
00:05:03,961 --> 00:05:06,243
opportunities, presentations, or exhibitions

115
00:05:06,283 --> 00:05:08,044
that DEI participants were involved in.

116
00:05:08,524 --> 00:05:11,686
And this included organizing monthly meetups,

117
00:05:12,286 --> 00:05:16,569
running or participating in game jams, speaking at conferences,

118
00:05:16,709 --> 00:05:18,891
applying for funding, exhibiting our games.

119
00:05:19,311 --> 00:05:22,793
And in addition to that, we did this work in our own time,

120
00:05:23,173 --> 00:05:25,054
and we made more games on top of that.

121
00:05:25,094 --> 00:05:26,395
So that's what failure looked like.

122
00:05:26,637 --> 00:05:28,541
It looks like maybe we should strive to fail more often.

123
00:05:30,785 --> 00:05:34,393
So meaningful cultural change is a slow process.

124
00:05:34,954 --> 00:05:35,535
It takes time.

125
00:05:36,438 --> 00:05:39,099
A six-week WIG program cannot change the industry overnight,

126
00:05:39,599 --> 00:05:42,401
but that really doesn't mean we should write off or give up

127
00:05:42,601 --> 00:05:45,102
on WIG initiatives as a lost cause.

128
00:05:45,202 --> 00:05:49,865
All too often, positive outcomes of initiatives like the DEI

129
00:05:49,945 --> 00:05:51,926
are forgotten, or they're overshadowed

130
00:05:51,966 --> 00:05:54,227
by this kind of thirst to tell and repeat bad news

131
00:05:54,267 --> 00:05:57,349
stories about women in games or women in games groups.

132
00:05:57,829 --> 00:05:59,910
And we all know these stories by heart now.

133
00:06:00,650 --> 00:06:02,631
Women are too sensitive or emotional.

134
00:06:02,711 --> 00:06:04,112
We need to grow thicker skin if we

135
00:06:04,152 --> 00:06:05,493
want to be a part of this industry.

136
00:06:06,847 --> 00:06:10,890
Diversity initiatives are negatively framed as handouts or special treatment.

137
00:06:10,910 --> 00:06:15,334
My personal favorite is that we're all feminist bitches who can't get along, and we'd rather

138
00:06:15,375 --> 00:06:16,976
tear each other down than build each other up.

139
00:06:17,817 --> 00:06:21,680
I don't know about you, but I think we need some new stories, and that's why we're here

140
00:06:21,700 --> 00:06:21,921
today.

141
00:06:23,002 --> 00:06:27,005
As participants, organizers, and supporters of diversity initiatives, we stand before

142
00:06:27,025 --> 00:06:30,268
you today as the best evidence that WIG programs can and do make a difference.

143
00:06:31,329 --> 00:06:34,431
And so without further ado, I'm really honoured to introduce the panelists.

144
00:06:35,031 --> 00:06:38,032
Sagan Yee is the Executive Director of the Hand Eye Society,

145
00:06:38,392 --> 00:06:40,033
the Video Games Art Collective in Toronto.

146
00:06:47,437 --> 00:06:51,079
Rebecca Cohen-Palacios is the co-founder and current director of Pixels.

147
00:06:57,438 --> 00:06:59,519
which is a Montreal-based wig group.

148
00:07:00,099 --> 00:07:02,461
She is also a dev at Ubisoft Montreal.

149
00:07:03,321 --> 00:07:05,582
Zoe Quinn is an independent game developer

150
00:07:05,622 --> 00:07:07,123
and the co-founder of Crash Override,

151
00:07:07,503 --> 00:07:09,084
a support network and assistance group

152
00:07:09,104 --> 00:07:10,705
for victims and targets of unique forms

153
00:07:10,745 --> 00:07:11,526
of online harassment.

154
00:07:11,546 --> 00:07:11,586
Oh.

155
00:07:11,606 --> 00:07:12,426
Thank you.

156
00:07:12,446 --> 00:07:12,626
Thank you.

157
00:07:12,646 --> 00:07:12,826
Thank you.

158
00:07:12,846 --> 00:07:13,026
Thank you.

159
00:07:13,046 --> 00:07:13,226
Thank you.

160
00:07:13,246 --> 00:07:13,427
Thank you.

161
00:07:13,447 --> 00:07:19,010
Thank you.

162
00:07:19,030 --> 00:07:21,271
And Gemma Thompson is an independent game designer.

163
00:07:22,334 --> 00:07:25,235
chair of Diversity Sweden, co-founder of Ladycade,

164
00:07:25,455 --> 00:07:27,476
and CheHack, two safe space communities

165
00:07:27,516 --> 00:07:29,136
which promote the enjoyment and creation

166
00:07:29,216 --> 00:07:30,337
of games, respectively.

167
00:07:30,357 --> 00:07:39,640
And so as this panel's gonna demonstrate,

168
00:07:39,680 --> 00:07:41,520
there's many paths to making WIG initiatives

169
00:07:41,620 --> 00:07:42,801
and diversity initiatives work,

170
00:07:42,921 --> 00:07:44,861
and they're not always straightforward or expected.

171
00:07:45,822 --> 00:07:47,502
Thank you, I will turn it over to Sagan.

172
00:07:53,677 --> 00:07:54,618
Hello, everyone.

173
00:07:54,958 --> 00:07:56,838
So I'm going to blast right through this.

174
00:07:56,858 --> 00:07:58,219
We don't have a lot of time.

175
00:07:58,559 --> 00:07:59,479
So I'm Sagan Yee.

176
00:07:59,539 --> 00:08:04,381
I'm executive director of the Hand Eye Society, which is a nonprofit arts organization dedicated

177
00:08:04,401 --> 00:08:07,522
to supporting video games made as a form of creative expression rather than a commercial

178
00:08:07,542 --> 00:08:07,942
product.

179
00:08:08,442 --> 00:08:12,503
And they're the ones that sort of organized the difference engine to begin with.

180
00:08:12,543 --> 00:08:15,184
So now that I'm actually running the show, it's kind of...

181
00:08:15,764 --> 00:08:17,945
this again, this whole circle motif.

182
00:08:18,185 --> 00:08:20,287
I didn't have time to put together an awesome ripple map,

183
00:08:20,967 --> 00:08:23,648
but I did kind of put together some major milestones

184
00:08:23,708 --> 00:08:27,911
in kind of my spiral-like journey to how I got here.

185
00:08:27,951 --> 00:08:30,172
And I think this is kind of important

186
00:08:30,192 --> 00:08:32,733
to show these professional and personal

187
00:08:32,953 --> 00:08:35,155
artistic trajectories to demonstrate the impact

188
00:08:35,375 --> 00:08:36,695
Difference Engine had on my life,

189
00:08:36,736 --> 00:08:38,096
because if it hadn't happened,

190
00:08:38,416 --> 00:08:40,057
none of the things I'm about to talk about

191
00:08:40,257 --> 00:08:40,858
would have happened.

192
00:08:40,898 --> 00:08:42,238
And I had a slide here with the poster

193
00:08:42,259 --> 00:08:44,580
for the butterfly effect with Ashton Kutcher's face on it,

194
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:45,440
and then I decided.

195
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:46,521
to not do that.

196
00:08:47,541 --> 00:08:50,682
So for some context, I just graduated.

197
00:08:50,702 --> 00:08:54,943
In 2011, I just graduated from a four-year classical animation

198
00:08:54,983 --> 00:08:55,403
program.

199
00:08:55,463 --> 00:08:57,144
I moved to Toronto with no job prospects

200
00:08:57,164 --> 00:08:58,384
and a lot of time on my hands.

201
00:08:59,104 --> 00:09:01,165
And I stumbled upon the application for DEI

202
00:09:01,205 --> 00:09:04,806
by randomly googling Toronto video games.

203
00:09:04,946 --> 00:09:07,127
And the first thing that came up was this application.

204
00:09:07,387 --> 00:09:09,908
And they were taking six women who had never made a game

205
00:09:09,928 --> 00:09:11,448
before who were interested in it.

206
00:09:12,089 --> 00:09:14,530
I signed up because it was free, there was going to be free food.

207
00:09:15,911 --> 00:09:22,475
Reason number one, one reason to be, I enjoyed playing games but I never really tried making

208
00:09:22,555 --> 00:09:26,297
one before and another thing I wasn't making was money and I had really nothing better

209
00:09:26,317 --> 00:09:26,637
to do.

210
00:09:27,398 --> 00:09:31,620
But also one major thing that I only realized later on was really important was that it

211
00:09:31,660 --> 00:09:33,422
was aimed specifically at women.

212
00:09:33,882 --> 00:09:38,064
Even though words like feminism and diversity weren't really on my radar at the time.

213
00:09:38,705 --> 00:09:42,906
I don't think that, I'm not sure I would have applied if it hadn't been just for women.

214
00:09:43,727 --> 00:09:46,588
That detail really caught my attention because it made me feel like my presence would be

215
00:09:46,648 --> 00:09:50,329
expected and accounted for and it wouldn't be yet another situation where I'd walk into

216
00:09:50,349 --> 00:09:54,830
the room and be the only woman there and have to navigate that situation socially by myself.

217
00:09:55,311 --> 00:09:58,732
And I was also working on like this earthbound animation that I don't have time to talk about.

218
00:10:00,452 --> 00:10:05,856
So, Difference Engine 1, I made my first game called Icarus, which you just saw.

219
00:10:06,036 --> 00:10:10,179
And we were barely finished with first Difference Engine when the coordinators asked me if I

220
00:10:10,199 --> 00:10:13,982
would like to be one of two Difference Engine 1 participants to lead the second version

221
00:10:14,022 --> 00:10:14,563
of the program.

222
00:10:15,003 --> 00:10:19,245
The second participant being Yuna Lee, who made the amazing Ripple graphics that you

223
00:10:19,285 --> 00:10:20,606
saw in the beginning.

224
00:10:20,846 --> 00:10:24,688
And I was like, I've only made one game in my life and it was the one I just made through

225
00:10:24,708 --> 00:10:29,331
your program and it's not even over yet and you're asking me to lead the second workshop?

226
00:10:29,351 --> 00:10:32,473
And they were like, yeah, yeah.

227
00:10:32,513 --> 00:10:36,895
And this was such a bold move on their part that I assumed they knew what they were doing.

228
00:10:38,087 --> 00:10:41,251
And so I don't necessarily think I was the most qualified person

229
00:10:41,271 --> 00:10:43,153
to co-lead that workshop, but everyone

230
00:10:43,173 --> 00:10:44,315
had a really positive time.

231
00:10:44,736 --> 00:10:47,279
And as we will hear, all six participants

232
00:10:47,319 --> 00:10:49,342
are still working in or around the games community

233
00:10:49,362 --> 00:10:51,344
to some degree, whether working in a studio

234
00:10:51,444 --> 00:10:54,088
or exhibiting their work at festivals or in Rebecca's case.

235
00:10:54,428 --> 00:10:56,009
co-founding their own organizations,

236
00:10:56,169 --> 00:10:57,850
and I've even collaborated with a few

237
00:10:57,890 --> 00:10:59,530
former participants on game projects.

238
00:11:00,831 --> 00:11:02,592
Again, I didn't make a Ripple tool.

239
00:11:02,692 --> 00:11:04,573
This was a six-week workshop for animators.

240
00:11:04,633 --> 00:11:07,494
I co-coordinated in 2014 with Matt Hamill,

241
00:11:07,514 --> 00:11:09,575
who's the artist on Lovers in a Dangerous Space-Time,

242
00:11:09,875 --> 00:11:12,336
and I bring this up briefly so I can mention Paloma Dawkins,

243
00:11:12,356 --> 00:11:14,537
who made her first game, Dream Warriors,

244
00:11:14,577 --> 00:11:16,638
through this program, and she later went on

245
00:11:16,658 --> 00:11:18,299
to make Gardenarium, which was showcased

246
00:11:18,319 --> 00:11:20,700
at GDC Mild Rumpus last year,

247
00:11:20,760 --> 00:11:22,501
as well as many other festivals and arcades,

248
00:11:22,541 --> 00:11:23,242
and that's like another,

249
00:11:23,642 --> 00:11:28,123
example of how someone goes through a WIG program and then they start running non-WIG programs,

250
00:11:28,203 --> 00:11:32,303
but it's still like women mentoring other women because you really want to like pay that forward.

251
00:11:33,564 --> 00:11:37,585
