499
00:24:07,342 --> 00:24:09,123
Some first-time game makers, everybody

500
00:24:09,223 --> 00:24:13,345
made their games in one month.

501
00:24:13,805 --> 00:24:15,286
We managed to publish it, and everybody got

502
00:24:15,386 --> 00:24:16,507
paid, which was super cool.

503
00:24:18,088 --> 00:24:20,229
The thing with these diversity initiatives

504
00:24:20,289 --> 00:24:22,310
is that you have to look at it like planting seeds.

505
00:24:22,771 --> 00:24:25,813
You might not see the benefit to it immediately,

506
00:24:25,873 --> 00:24:27,233
because these things need to grow.

507
00:24:27,674 --> 00:24:29,835
And as we grow these, it's important to remember

508
00:24:29,875 --> 00:24:31,536
to try to tend our garden as we do it.

509
00:24:32,850 --> 00:24:37,651
If there's one thing all of these diversity efforts could do, I would also ask to encourage

510
00:24:37,691 --> 00:24:41,412
participants to make their own spaces if they enter the industry and still feel like they

511
00:24:41,452 --> 00:24:43,972
might not belong here, because so many of us have.

512
00:24:44,492 --> 00:24:49,673
And I feel like when independent projects like this happen and actively reach out to

513
00:24:49,713 --> 00:24:53,874
communities and say, you can do this, we come from a place where we start with that level

514
00:24:54,014 --> 00:24:57,435
of, oh, awesome, I can do this, that means other people can do this, let's help other

515
00:24:57,475 --> 00:24:58,095
people do this.

516
00:24:58,595 --> 00:25:00,375
And that's something that gets overlooked a little bit.

517
00:25:00,796 --> 00:25:03,678
that this sort of cascading effect happens.

518
00:25:04,118 --> 00:25:05,599
We start with the belief that it can be done,

519
00:25:05,799 --> 00:25:07,140
that it's fine to be weird.

520
00:25:07,440 --> 00:25:09,061
We are all fucking weirdos anyway.

521
00:25:09,121 --> 00:25:10,582
And telling people that they can build things

522
00:25:10,642 --> 00:25:12,083
for people that are their kind of weird

523
00:25:12,123 --> 00:25:14,805
is a really empowering thing to do alongside game development.

524
00:25:15,566 --> 00:25:17,607
But in the meantime, I'm focusing,

525
00:25:17,707 --> 00:25:19,748
trying to figure out how to make more women

526
00:25:19,988 --> 00:25:22,310
and basically make more people that

527
00:25:22,350 --> 00:25:25,872
are dealing with any kind of oppression in the games

528
00:25:25,912 --> 00:25:26,773
industry stay.

529
00:25:26,873 --> 00:25:28,994
So going beyond just these starting conversations.

530
00:25:30,425 --> 00:25:31,405
and trying to mentor people.

531
00:25:31,445 --> 00:25:34,547
Mentorship should go beyond just the initial things,

532
00:25:34,587 --> 00:25:36,168
because once you get here, it's very easy

533
00:25:36,188 --> 00:25:39,090
to have so many questions, like, how do I negotiate a contract?

534
00:25:39,430 --> 00:25:40,630
What does porting look like?

535
00:25:41,051 --> 00:25:43,792
All these things to not just run and start these things,

536
00:25:43,852 --> 00:25:44,913
but to continue forward.

537
00:25:45,533 --> 00:25:47,274
And I'd like to see more women stay.

538
00:25:47,434 --> 00:25:49,135
I'd like to see more women held up

539
00:25:49,215 --> 00:25:51,116
as auteurs and leaders and visionaries

540
00:25:51,416 --> 00:25:53,417
for their amazing work, and not just the bad shit that

541
00:25:53,457 --> 00:25:54,158
happens to us.

542
00:25:54,678 --> 00:25:56,779
I'd like to see them flourish, and not just survive.

543
00:25:57,290 --> 00:25:59,251
I'd like to see them not have to fight the same battles we

544
00:25:59,311 --> 00:26:02,093
already have or on other fronts of marginalization.

545
00:26:02,233 --> 00:26:05,054
Because at the end of the day, despite the legendarily hard

546
00:26:05,094 --> 00:26:07,576
time I've had in this industry, learning how to make games

547
00:26:07,616 --> 00:26:09,177
is still the best thing that's ever happened to me.

548
00:26:09,197 --> 00:26:11,418
Thank you.

549
00:26:11,438 --> 00:26:12,938
Thank you.

550
00:26:12,978 --> 00:26:16,380
Thank you.

551
00:26:16,400 --> 00:26:22,643
Thank you.

552
00:26:22,664 --> 00:26:22,844
Thank you.

553
00:26:22,864 --> 00:26:23,344
Thank you.

554
00:26:23,364 --> 00:26:23,564
Thank you.

555
00:26:23,584 --> 00:26:23,644
Hey.

556
00:26:24,212 --> 00:26:25,553
Yes, my name is Gemma Thompson.

557
00:26:25,893 --> 00:26:26,873
I'm a game designer.

558
00:26:27,334 --> 00:26:29,355
And as you could probably tell by my accent,

559
00:26:29,415 --> 00:26:31,015
I'm not even from the same continent

560
00:26:31,055 --> 00:26:31,996
as the rest of the panelists.

561
00:26:32,916 --> 00:26:35,157
But I did find that my experiences

562
00:26:35,217 --> 00:26:37,798
in games culture in the industry have actually strongly echoed

563
00:26:38,018 --> 00:26:38,299
theirs.

564
00:26:39,599 --> 00:26:42,580
My career began really with a game design degree course

565
00:26:42,720 --> 00:26:45,382
in which there were four women to some 46 men.

566
00:26:46,442 --> 00:26:48,663
But things took a more prominent turn

567
00:26:48,703 --> 00:26:51,284
when I signed up to Europe's first all-female game jam

568
00:26:51,324 --> 00:26:51,384
in 2012.

569
00:26:53,024 --> 00:26:55,265
That experience instilled new confidence in my work,

570
00:26:55,906 --> 00:26:58,007
it started lasting friendships within this profession,

571
00:26:58,708 --> 00:27:01,370
and despite that gender segregated premise,

572
00:27:01,550 --> 00:27:03,351
it reassured me that I could actually engage

573
00:27:03,591 --> 00:27:05,432
in male dominated game culture,

574
00:27:05,573 --> 00:27:06,833
or at least as it was perceived.

575
00:27:07,694 --> 00:27:10,136
I stand now in 2016 as chair of Diversee,

576
00:27:10,376 --> 00:27:12,217
an organization which works extensively

577
00:27:12,257 --> 00:27:14,299
with companies, communities, and individuals,

578
00:27:14,399 --> 00:27:15,680
primarily in the Nordic region,

579
00:27:16,480 --> 00:27:18,141
to promote and support a broad range

580
00:27:18,161 --> 00:27:20,063
of diversity efforts in and around games.

581
00:27:20,837 --> 00:27:25,122
More relevant to this panel, however, I'm also the co-founder of three separate initiatives,

582
00:27:25,282 --> 00:27:30,288
which, as I'm about to explain, have encouraged game creation and the celebration of games

583
00:27:30,528 --> 00:27:35,674
amongst hundreds of new, shy, or disheartened female-identifying individuals across Northern

584
00:27:35,774 --> 00:27:35,995
Europe.

585
00:27:37,554 --> 00:27:41,518
So in my case, it all began in a 24-hour Game Jam event

586
00:27:41,558 --> 00:27:42,038
in London.

587
00:27:42,338 --> 00:27:43,759
It was supported by a number of bodies,

588
00:27:43,840 --> 00:27:46,101
including the UK's Next Gen Skills campaign.

589
00:27:47,042 --> 00:27:48,524
And it's called XX Game Jam.

590
00:27:48,644 --> 00:27:50,705
It was an all-female event arranged

591
00:27:50,725 --> 00:27:52,867
to coincide with Ada Lovelace Day in October 2012.

592
00:27:52,967 --> 00:27:56,971
It led to the creation of six rather wonderfully varied

593
00:27:57,011 --> 00:27:59,113
games, including the first one I could actually

594
00:27:59,173 --> 00:28:01,375
claim to have been involved in from start to finish.

595
00:28:03,347 --> 00:28:05,168
It was also the first game jam I'd ever attended.

596
00:28:05,908 --> 00:28:08,029
And as I said, the friendships I forged here

597
00:28:08,049 --> 00:28:10,150
had to reach well beyond the British shoreline.

598
00:28:11,270 --> 00:28:14,311
I have worked with XS Game Jam alumni at other events,

599
00:28:14,371 --> 00:28:16,912
including List Summit in Copenhagen and Helsinki,

600
00:28:17,672 --> 00:28:18,433
and Anthology Jam.

601
00:28:20,333 --> 00:28:22,074
XS Game Jam also led three of us

602
00:28:22,174 --> 00:28:24,495
to found a women in games initiative of our own.

603
00:28:26,075 --> 00:28:27,636
That initiative is called Ladycade,

604
00:28:28,116 --> 00:28:30,037
and I've been running it since 2013

605
00:28:30,217 --> 00:28:31,977
with Holly Pickering and Ennis McKendrick.

606
00:28:32,866 --> 00:28:37,009
It's an event which has steadily gathered more pace as years have gone on,

607
00:28:37,490 --> 00:28:40,652
and it's founded on the simple idea that women who make and enjoy games

608
00:28:40,712 --> 00:28:43,294
deserve a hangout space where they can feel safe and comfortable,

609
00:28:43,734 --> 00:28:46,176
but need not worry about being a woman in industry.

610
00:28:47,537 --> 00:28:51,220
Nor will they have to spend the entire evening discussing how to get more women involved.

611
00:28:52,501 --> 00:28:55,683
What we do is we hold social events and games showcases,

612
00:28:56,404 --> 00:28:57,905
to which all genders are invited,

613
00:28:58,225 --> 00:29:00,567
but where the attendee demographic is at least 50% female.

614
00:29:02,411 --> 00:29:05,573
as in these snapshots of our first event in Nottingham

615
00:29:05,873 --> 00:29:08,154
and later on in London, which is the one shown on the right.

616
00:29:10,415 --> 00:29:12,176
Thus far, we've held seven gatherings,

617
00:29:12,316 --> 00:29:15,037
either as stand-alones or alongside an existing event.

618
00:29:15,718 --> 00:29:18,919
We've worked to create events for three years running

619
00:29:18,979 --> 00:29:20,120
at Game City in Nottingham,

620
00:29:20,540 --> 00:29:21,901
and we opened up last year's

621
00:29:21,961 --> 00:29:23,242
Creative Coast Festival in Sweden.

622
00:29:24,232 --> 00:29:26,554
Roughly 450 attendees have come to these,

623
00:29:27,074 --> 00:29:28,695
enjoying an atmosphere which many have described

624
00:29:28,735 --> 00:29:29,856
as disarmingly friendly.

625
00:29:30,377 --> 00:29:32,418
And this tends to be a sentiment shared mostly

626
00:29:32,458 --> 00:29:34,140
by the men in attendance, who we've

627
00:29:34,180 --> 00:29:36,902
found to be just as tired as we are of nigh-on gender

628
00:29:36,922 --> 00:29:37,843
homogenous events.

629
00:29:39,044 --> 00:29:41,486
Many of these attendees have also partaken

630
00:29:41,526 --> 00:29:44,529
of the games we showcase, indie titles being made by women,

631
00:29:44,729 --> 00:29:46,690
some of whom have never demonstrated on a show floor

632
00:29:46,710 --> 00:29:50,213
before, but have been encouraged to do so at a Lady Kade arcade.

633
00:29:50,233 --> 00:29:53,336
And that particular initiative works towards two goals.

634
00:29:53,780 --> 00:29:56,142
providing a platform so that more women can feel at ease

635
00:29:56,182 --> 00:29:57,503
showcasing their games like that,

636
00:29:58,023 --> 00:30:00,285
and tangibly proving that women are, of course,

637
00:30:00,445 --> 00:30:02,807
in these local communities making excellent things.

638
00:30:03,648 --> 00:30:05,650
It's this last point which I feel most strongly

639
00:30:05,710 --> 00:30:08,192
harkens back to my experience of the XS Game Jam.

640
00:30:09,072 --> 00:30:10,754
And it's hard for me to understate

641
00:30:10,774 --> 00:30:13,016
the importance of this visibility on a personal level,

642
00:30:13,396 --> 00:30:14,917
not least because, as I mentioned,

643
00:30:15,017 --> 00:30:17,079
that was the first one I felt comfortable attending.

644
00:30:17,712 --> 00:30:19,713
I knew jamming to be a challenging activity.

645
00:30:19,833 --> 00:30:22,796
And having previously not felt comfortable dealing

646
00:30:22,856 --> 00:30:25,558
with gross gender disparity at these events as well,

647
00:30:25,899 --> 00:30:27,640
it added a bit of a relief, to be honest.

648
00:30:30,062 --> 00:30:31,964
Well, I can proudly say that game jamming is now

649
00:30:32,044 --> 00:30:32,945
one of the things I do.

650
00:30:33,365 --> 00:30:35,407
It's a productive hobby, which has taken me

651
00:30:35,467 --> 00:30:36,488
all over northern Europe.

652
00:30:36,948 --> 00:30:38,990
And it's taught me much about rapid iteration

653
00:30:39,050 --> 00:30:40,071
elemental game design.

654
00:30:40,792 --> 00:30:42,653
As someone with very little coding ability,

655
00:30:42,673 --> 00:30:44,134
it's also been an excellent way for me

656
00:30:44,175 --> 00:30:45,716
to keep making games outside of work.

657
00:30:46,939 --> 00:30:51,043
I overcame that initial confidence barrier after having embarrassment about my gender

658
00:30:51,083 --> 00:30:52,284
removed from the equation.

659
00:30:52,664 --> 00:30:54,246
But the same can't be said for everyone.

660
00:30:54,726 --> 00:30:58,970
In the same way that Lady K draws exhibitors and creators out into a community which they

661
00:30:59,010 --> 00:31:03,394
then realize can be inclusive, I resolve to do the same for Game Jams.

662
00:31:04,895 --> 00:31:09,960
So as a sideways step, I am co-founder and vice chair of Game Jam Stockholm, a non-profit

663
00:31:09,980 --> 00:31:11,541
which bears its purpose in its name.

664
00:31:12,127 --> 00:31:17,631
We've run five events of various sizes so far, and although our actual demographics do vary between events,

665
00:31:18,052 --> 00:31:19,613
the general format has been the same.

666
00:31:19,973 --> 00:31:22,355
Positive outreach towards genders other than male,

667
00:31:22,875 --> 00:31:27,138
assuaging the fears of those who haven't jammed before and feel their skills aren't up to the challenge,

668
00:31:27,618 --> 00:31:33,062
and ensuring we have sufficiently safe spaces and the facilities to cater for vulnerable people from many walks of life.

669
00:31:33,903 --> 00:31:38,326
These efforts are being played out long term, since one cannot conjure up a diverse community from nothing.

670
00:31:39,738 --> 00:31:46,344
And in Game Jam Stockholm's case, we worked to ensure that the Swedish capital fosters a steadily more inclusive jamming scene.

671
00:31:47,705 --> 00:31:51,348
To that end, here's a rough breakdown of the gender split at our larger events.

672
00:31:51,949 --> 00:31:56,613
Women and non-binary people are represented by the orange and black sections at the top left of each graph.

673
00:32:02,378 --> 00:32:07,262
After less than two years of operation, it is of course hard to project any sort of meaningful trends here.

674
00:32:07,693 --> 00:32:12,757
But the bottom line is that we are bringing more women and girls into this hobby and the local game jam scene.

675
00:32:13,277 --> 00:32:19,742
We find, for example, that word will spread amongst student bodies and local studios, encouraging more of the women there to join in.

676
00:32:20,622 --> 00:32:28,127
A huge driver for this trend is also Game Jam Stockholm's collaboration with another outreach organization, which specifically supports girls and women in making games.

677
00:32:29,691 --> 00:32:35,534
Myself and Game Jam Stockholm's Inger Ekman are also co-founders of Chehack, a nationwide

678
00:32:35,554 --> 00:32:39,815
scheme in Sweden which runs regular game creation clubs and events for girls and women.

679
00:32:40,676 --> 00:32:45,818
It began in 2014 with a free weekly after school club in a suburb outside of Stockholm's

680
00:32:45,858 --> 00:32:46,498
city centre.

681
00:32:46,959 --> 00:32:51,020
And this intentional move to bring game creation to families in the less social mobile paid

682
00:32:51,121 --> 00:32:55,142
huge dividends, particularly for the girls we have involved, who are aged from generally

683
00:32:55,202 --> 00:32:55,563
like 8 to 16.

684
00:32:56,995 --> 00:32:59,536
It's a pattern we hope to repeat in the wake of our recently

685
00:32:59,576 --> 00:33:02,718
completed nationwide tour, which took in seven towns and cities

686
00:33:02,778 --> 00:33:04,079
across mid and southern Sweden.

687
00:33:05,220 --> 00:33:06,781
Of those women we've involved in the club,

688
00:33:06,841 --> 00:33:09,503
two have recently rejoined games-related education

689
00:33:09,743 --> 00:33:12,064
on paths towards professional programming and art,

690
00:33:12,104 --> 00:33:12,725
respectively.

691
00:33:13,265 --> 00:33:16,047
We've also eased theirs and other members' paths

692
00:33:16,087 --> 00:33:17,288
into local game jam events.

693
00:33:18,088 --> 00:33:20,490
What began with a girls and women-only pajama jam

694
00:33:20,630 --> 00:33:22,471
at the Royal College of Technology in Stockholm

695
00:33:22,760 --> 00:33:25,761
became a 29-member strong mentor-led delegation

696
00:33:25,881 --> 00:33:28,022
at Global Game Jam Stockholm 2016.

697
00:33:28,722 --> 00:33:30,923
The Chehackers got stuck into all manner of games,

698
00:33:31,083 --> 00:33:32,924
including the one I've got running on a hat,

699
00:33:33,484 --> 00:33:36,086
running on a Gemma Arduino, which I'll be showing later.

700
00:33:38,447 --> 00:33:40,808
And that's primarily the handwork of Inge Ekman

701
00:33:40,828 --> 00:33:41,728
and Amandine Coget.

702
00:33:43,109 --> 00:33:44,830
It's worth saying that with events like this

703
00:33:45,170 --> 00:33:48,111
and Chehack's regular club meetings, our goal,

704
00:33:48,251 --> 00:33:51,012
as with Ladycade, is not to train or push for more women

705
00:33:51,032 --> 00:33:52,033
to enter the industry.

706
00:33:52,824 --> 00:33:54,705
Nor are we really there to educate.

707
00:33:55,005 --> 00:33:56,646
Instead, we promote the creation of games

708
00:33:56,706 --> 00:33:58,467
as an interesting endeavor in and of itself,

709
00:33:58,928 --> 00:34:01,589
and simply find that as a natural extension of that,

710
00:34:01,930 --> 00:34:03,251
these girls and women in Sweden

711
00:34:03,451 --> 00:34:05,312
are having their eyes open to vocations

712
00:34:05,392 --> 00:34:07,353
in game development and other related fields.

713
00:34:09,195 --> 00:34:11,076
This is the essence of the ripple effect for me,

714
00:34:11,176 --> 00:34:12,997
which I've just represented as a transit map.

715
00:34:14,474 --> 00:34:17,975
At XH Game Jam, I joined a practical and creative exercise

716
00:34:18,015 --> 00:34:20,076
which had previously appeared hostile to my gender.

717
00:34:20,436 --> 00:34:22,797
In the end, I was reassured both in my abilities

718
00:34:22,937 --> 00:34:25,517
and in my right to create in all kinds of subtle ways.

719
00:34:26,238 --> 00:34:28,558
And I've since spread that rather pure message to others.

720
00:34:29,298 --> 00:34:32,639
In working with Diva C, I strive to pass that on for message,

721
00:34:33,560 --> 00:34:35,060
strive to pass that message on

722
00:34:35,140 --> 00:34:36,461
for folks from other walks of life,

723
00:34:36,861 --> 00:34:38,581
and indeed get involved in explicitly bringing

724
00:34:38,621 --> 00:34:39,702
more women into industry,

725
00:34:40,042 --> 00:34:41,642
as with our GDC scholarship this year.

726
00:34:42,754 --> 00:34:46,879
Ultimately though, it seems that a gentler splash and smaller outward ripples have managed

727
00:34:46,899 --> 00:34:51,785
to travel quite far enough for me and the things I've been working on, given that Stockholm

728
00:34:51,805 --> 00:34:53,988
is like 8,600 kilometers away now.

729
00:34:54,008 --> 00:34:56,411
And that is basically me.

730
00:35:07,098 --> 00:35:08,079
Thank you everybody.

731
00:35:08,099 --> 00:35:14,324
I think everyone's eager to have us talk about strategies

732
00:35:14,584 --> 00:35:15,585
and takeaway points.

733
00:35:17,386 --> 00:35:22,230
So I guess my first question is, what are some strategies

734
00:35:22,350 --> 00:35:24,532
that you guys can share from your experiences

735
00:35:24,572 --> 00:35:27,914
that you want to share with the audience?

736
00:35:29,295 --> 00:35:30,156
Who wants to go first?

737
00:35:33,764 --> 00:35:49,321
I guess I can go first. So leading up to this panel and we were talking about, well, people will probably want to come away with some really concrete strategies for increasing women in their group or finding the women who are probably already there.

738
00:35:50,772 --> 00:35:54,076
Um, and so some interesting kind of observations came up.

739
00:35:54,117 --> 00:35:57,661
I'm going to name some of them and then maybe you guys can like chip in as well.

740
00:35:57,741 --> 00:36:02,947
But, um, like I kind of noticed that, um, because I run a non-wig organization,

741
00:36:02,967 --> 00:36:04,549
I'm suddenly facing.

742
00:36:05,430 --> 00:36:07,131
like, a lot of the challenges of like,

743
00:36:07,751 --> 00:36:09,231
because I've inherited this organization that's,

744
00:36:09,651 --> 00:36:13,792
that was pretty homogenous in terms of gender,

745
00:36:13,932 --> 00:36:15,673
like it's mostly male, mostly white males,

746
00:36:16,353 --> 00:36:18,173
